    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1672103838" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1672103838" />
    <a title="Manny" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1713956-manny"><img alt="Manny" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442491692p2/1713956.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1672103838?book_show_action=true">Jun 18, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Manny" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Manny" href="/user/show/1713956-manny">Manny</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1713956-manny?shelf=donalds-are-trumps">donalds-are-trumps</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1672103838" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14966445757208137726">Like many people, I could hardly believe my eyes when Donald Trump, in the wake of the Orlando shooting, actually went as far as to insinuate that President Obama could in some way have been complicit in causing this appalling hate crime and act of terrorism. The idea is so offensive and absurd that you hardly know where to start. A common reaction has been to point out that, if Obama is on the side of the terrorists, you&apos;d have to explain why he&apos;d want to invest so much effort in killing Osama </span>
  <span id="freeText14966445757208137726" style="display:none">Like many people, I could hardly believe my eyes when Donald Trump, in the wake of the Orlando shooting, actually went as far as to insinuate that President Obama could in some way have been complicit in causing this appalling hate crime and act of terrorism. The idea is so offensive and absurd that you hardly know where to start. A common reaction has been to point out that, if Obama is on the side of the terrorists, you'd have to explain why he'd want to invest so much effort in killing Osama bin Laden, not to mention authorizing thousands of drone strikes. To me, an even stronger counter-argument is <i>cui bono</i>. Just what hidden agenda would Obama be trying to progress by allowing this hideous crime to happen? <br /><br />But, and I freely admit it, I'm behind the times: conspiracy theory is the new black. I suppose I need to catch up, so let me ask what makes us so sure that <i>Trump</i> is in the clear? Unlike Obama, he has an obvious reason for wanting events like Orlando to happen: they help his campaign, which is largely fuelled by polarizing narratives of "us" against "them". He was remarkably quick in reacting to the news, and hardly even bothered to express shock or sympathy with the victims before he started harvesting political capital. All in all, he behaved pretty much exactly the way he'd have behaved if he had in fact been behind it.<br /><br />Well, I'm not saying Trump <i>was</i> the guy behind Omar Mateen. But I'm not saying he wasn't either. As you can see, there's a case, and I'd like to hear him deny it in so many words... which, to the best of my knowledge, he hasn't yet done. Suspicious or what?<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14966445757208137726" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


