              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6343232532178885042">The author evolved from being a theologically-trained, believing Christian to becoming a leader of the Skeptics Society. This book consists of essays about such pseudo-sciences as Objectivism, Creation-science, Holocaust-denial, UFOlogy and the like. For me the most interesting part was his review of the Holocaust debate, the most disappointing his treatment of what our government now calls &apos;unidentified aerial phenomena&apos;. Throughout Shermer maintains a sense of humor and tolerance.</span>
  <span id="freeText6343232532178885042" style="display:none">The author evolved from being a theologically-trained, believing Christian to becoming a leader of the Skeptics Society. This book consists of essays about such pseudo-sciences as Objectivism, Creation-science, Holocaust-denial, UFOlogy and the like. For me the most interesting part was his review of the Holocaust debate, the most disappointing his treatment of what our government now calls 'unidentified aerial phenomena'. Throughout Shermer maintains a sense of humor and tolerance.</span>
